<div id="content_text">



<!-- inc publications_db -->

 <strong>October 24,  2013</strong><p><strong>UC Irvine opens the Institute for Virtual Environments and Computer Games</strong><p>


<p>
Irvine, Calif., Oct. 24, 2013 &mdash; Building on UC Irvine&rsquo;s 
reputation as one of the top U.S. institutions for computer game science, 
the campus has established the 
<a href="http://ivecg.uci.edu">Institute for Virtual Environments and Computer Games</a>, 
a multidisciplinary Organized Research Unit.</p>



<object width="400" height="300"> <param name="flashvars" value="offsite=true&lang=en-us&page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157636886206233%2Fshow%2F&page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157636886206233%2F&set_id=72157636886206233&jump_to="></param> <param name="movie" value="http://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=124984"></param> <param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="http://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=124984" allowFullScreen="true" flashvars="offsite=true&lang=en-us&page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157636886206233%2Fshow%2F&page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157636886206233%2F&set_id=72157636886206233&jump_to=" width="400" height="300"></embed></object>



<p>
As the newest of UC Irvine&rsquo;s 
<a href="https://apps.research.uci.edu/centers/researchPrograms.cfm?ru_type_cd=ORU">18 ORUs</a>, 
the institute seeks to revolutionize how people teach, learn, conduct business, provide health care and interact in society. </p>
<p>
Institute director Magda El Zarki said the IVECG&rsquo;s ability to marry the work of faculty from the UCI 
<a href="http://www.ics.uci.edu">Donald Bren School of Information and Computer Sciences</a> 
with that of scholars from other academic disciplines will drive the institute&rsquo;s research in new and exciting directions.</p>
<p>
&ldquo;People are more aware of and involved in gaming, and are taking it beyond just entertainment,&rdquo; said El Zarki, professor of 
<a href="http://www.cs.uci.edu">computer science</a> 
at the Bren School. &ldquo;Virtual environments are being used widely for many different purposes such as training, real-time simulations, health, scientific visualization, 
remote collaborations, conferences and education &mdash; as well as socializing and high-end online gaming.&rdquo;</p>
<p>
IVECG research director Walt Scacchi (Ph.D. &rsquo;81) said faculty interest in the institute is &ldquo;coming from pretty much all of the schools at the university, and that&rsquo;s not common for an 
ORU. Artists, biologists, humanities professors, engineers &mdash; they&rsquo;re all saying, &lsquo;Hey this video-game thing is interesting, count me in.&rsquo; &rdquo;</p>
<p>
The academic diversity of the institute should also attract increased student participation in its projects, El Zarki said, including the school&rsquo;s 
<a href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/prospective/en/degrees/computer-game-science/">computer game science</a> 
majors and members of such student groups as the 
<a href="http://vgdc-uci.com">Video Game Development Club</a>.</p>
<p>
Research at the institute is based in three areas: technology and design; society and culture; and applications and education. The institute has received a $500,000 grant over its first five years, 
most of which, El Zarki said, will be spent on starting up new interdisciplinary projects.</p>
<p>
In one such endeavor, El Zarki has teamed up with Patricia Seed, professor of 
<a href="http://www.humanities.uci.edu/history/">history</a>, 
to create a virtual, three-dimensional, interactive map that allows 
students to explore, in an immersive environment, the slave trade on 
the African continent from 1400-1700 CE. In teaching the history of 
the slave trade and the arrival of Africans to American shores, nearly 
all of the scholarship has focused upon the journey across the Atlantic 
and the dreadful fate that awaited the slaves once they reached the 
New World. However, the people who were transported across the Atlantic 
were born into distinct societies, cultures, families and customs that 
had endured for decades and sometimes centuries. This interactive virtual 
environment will offer students a way to understand that deeper context.</p>

<p>
Scacchi is part of a research team that includes professors from the Department of 
<a href="http://www.informatics.uci.edu">Informatics</a>, 
Department of 
<a href="http://www.neurology.uci.edu">Neurology</a> 
in the School of Medicine, and the Program 
in 
<a href="http://www.nursing.uci.edu">Nursing Science</a> 
to study therapeutic applications 
of games. Some, for example, help patients recovering from a stroke 
or living with asthma and other chronic ailments learn how to better 
manage their conditions.</p>

<p>&ldquo;The Institute for Virtual Environments and Computer Games enhances UC Irvine&rsquo;s position 
as a leader in computer game research,&rdquo; said Hal Stern, the Bren School&rsquo;s 
Ted and Janice Smith Family Foundation Dean. &ldquo;As the two examples 
above make clear, it is about much more than entertainment. Computer 
games and virtual environments are now playing a significant role in 
training, education, marketing and health.&rdquo;</p>

<p>
<STRONG>About the UC Irvine Donald Bren School of Information and Computer Sciences:</STRONG> 
As the only computing-focused school in the University 
of California system, the Bren School is providing computer science 
and information technology leadership for the 21st century through its 
innovative and broad curricula, research and development of emerging 
technologies, and collaborations to address societal concerns. For more 
information, visit:
<a href="http://www.ics.uci.edu">www.ics.uci.edu</a></p>

<p>
<STRONG>About the University of California, Irvine:</STRONG> 
Located in coastal Orange County, near a thriving 
employment hub in one of the nation&rsquo;s safest cities, UC Irvine was 
founded in 1965. One of only 62 members of the Association of American 
Universities, it&rsquo;s ranked first among U.S. universities under 50 years 
old by the London-based Times Higher Education. The campus has produced 
three Nobel laureates and is known for its academic achievement, premier 
research, innovation and anteater mascot. Led by 
<a href="http://chancellor.uci.edu">Chancellor Michael Drake</a>
since 2005, UC Irvine has more than 28,000 students 
and offers 192 degree programs. It&rsquo;s Orange County&rsquo;s second-largest 
employer, contributing $4.3 billion annually to the local economy.</p>



<p>
<b>CONTACT:</b><br>	
Rizza Barnes <BR>
Phone: (949) 824-1562 <BR>
<a href="mailto:rizza.barnes@uci.edu">rizza.barnes@uci.edu</a>






<br>

</div>
</blockquote>
